  "text": "## Kubernetes Lease-Based Leader Election\n\n### Architecture\nKubernetes implements leader election using **Kubernetes Lease API** as the coordination mechanism. Components (like kube-controller-manager, kube-scheduler) compete for leadership by updating Lease objects in the Kubernetes API server.\n\n### Key Components\n\n**1. LeaderElector (staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/leaderelection.go)**\n- Main client responsible for acquiring and renewing leadership leases\n- Operates with three time-based parameters: LeaseDuration, RenewDeadline, RetryPeriod\n- Maintains observedRecord tracking current lease holder identity\n\n**2. LeaderElectionRecord (staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/resourcelock/interface.go)**\n- Stores: HolderIdentity, AcquireTime, RenewTime, LeaseDurationSeconds, LeaderTransitions\n- Transitions count increments each time leadership changes, useful for detecting failovers\n\n**3. Lease-Based Coordination (pkg/apis/coordination/types.go)**\n- Uses Kubernetes Lease API (coordination.k8s.io/v1)\n- Modern approach also supports Coordinated Leader Election with LeaseCandidate objects for picking best leader\n- Supports multiple election strategies: OldestEmulationVersion strategy for version-aware selection\n\n### Leadership Acquisition and Renewal Flow\n\n**Acquisition Phase (leaderelection.go:acquire())**\n- Loops calling tryAcquireOrRenew() with exponential backoff (RetryPeriod base, 1.2x jitter)\n- First successful update creates the lease or updates it if expired\n\n**Renewal Phase (leaderelection.go:renew())**\n- Leader continuously renews within RenewDeadline timeout\n- Fast path: Optimistic update using last observed record\n- Slow path: Fetch fresh record, verify ownership, then update\n- Updates RenewTime to extend lease validity\n\n**Failover Detection (leaderelection.go:isLeaseValid())**\n- Non-leaders observe lease and detect expiry\n- Lease expires when: RenewTime + LeaseDurationSeconds < now\n- Failed leader detected when renewals fail (e.g., leader unreachable, cannot reach API server)\n- Default timings: LeaseDuration=15s, RenewDeadline=10s, RetryPeriod=2s\n\n### Health Monitoring\n- HealthzAdaptor tracks if current leader is failing to renew within tolerance\n- LeaderCallbacks notify: OnStartedLeading, OnStoppedLeading, OnNewLeader\n- Metrics track leader_election_master_status and slowpath_total\n\n---\n\n## etcd Raft-Based Leader Election\n\n### Architecture\netcd uses **Raft consensus protocol** for leader election. All nodes participate in a distributed consensus algorithm where only one node can be elected as leader for each term.\n\n### Key Components\n\n**1. RaftNode (server/etcdserver/raft.go)**\n- Wraps go.etcd.io/raft/v3 library\n- Executes ticker loop that periodically calls raft.Tick() for election timeout\n- Transitions happen via Raft state machine: Follower → Candidate → Leader\n- Manages heartbeat intervals and election timeouts\n\n**2. EtcdServer (server/etcdserver/server.go)**\n- Top-level server implementing leader detection and failover\n- Methods: Lead() returns current leader ID, isLeader() checks if local is leader\n- Tracks leadership changes via raftStatus.Lead field (updated from Raft Ready messages)\n\n**3. Leadership Tracking (server/etcdserver/raft.go:start())**\n- Monitors SoftState.Lead from Raft Ready channel\n- Detects leader changes and fires updateLeadership callback\n- Sets metrics: hasLeader (1/0), isLeader (1/0), leaderChanges counter\n\n### Leadership Election Mechanism\n\n**Election Trigger (server/config/config.go)**\n- Followers track ElectionTicks (default 10 ticks)\n- Each tick = TickMs (default 100ms), so election timeout ≈ 1 second\n- InitialElectionTickAdvance: Fast-forwards ticks on startup to speed initial election\n- PreVote: Additional phase to minimize disruptive re-elections\n\n**State Transitions (Raft-driven)**\n- **Follower**: Receives heartbeats (AppendEntries) from leader\n- **Candidate**: On election timeout, campaigns for votes\n- **Leader**: Wins majority votes, becomes leader and sends heartbeats to all followers\n\n**Failover Detection (server/etcdserver/raft.go:start())**\n- Followers timeout if no heartbeat within ElectionTicks duration\n- New candidate wins election among remaining nodes\n- Followers detect new leader from updated SoftState.Lead\n- Raft guarantees only one leader per term through strict voting rules\n\n### Leadership Transfer\n\n**Explicit Transfer (server/etcdserver/server.go:MoveLeader())**\n- Current leader manually transfers leadership to target member\n- Validates target is not a learner (learners cannot be leaders)\n- Uses raft.TransferLeadership() to initiate transfer\n- Waits for Lead() to change to target before returning\n\n**Graceful Shutdown (server/etcdserver/server.go:TryTransferLeadershipOnShutdown())**\n- On shutdown, current leader transfers to longest-connected follower\n- Prevents abrupt leader loss in multi-node clusters\n- Single-node clusters skip transfer (no targets available)\n- Timeout: ReqTimeout from configuration\n\n### Health and Monitoring\n- LeaderStats tracks communication with each follower\n- Heartbeat send failures indicate overloaded disk or network issues\n- Interceptor (server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go) checks s.Leader() != raft.None\n- Metrics track leader_changes_seen_total per day\n\n---\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Aspect | Kubernetes | etcd |\n|--------|-----------|------|\n| **Mechanism** | Lease-based (API objects) | Raft-based (consensus) |\n| **Timing** | LeaseDuration (15s default) | ElectionTicks (1s default) |\n| **Failover Detection** | Lease expiration check | Heartbeat timeout in Raft |\n| **Coordination** | Kubernetes API server | Direct peer-to-peer Raft messages |\n| **Re-election** | Any expired lease can be acquired | Raft voting ensures safety |\n| **Transfer** | Manual or timeout-based | MoveLeader() API or graceful shutdown |\n| **Fault Tolerance** | Depends on API server availability | Byzantine-resilient consensus |\n| **Scale** | Works for many small clusters | Optimized for single etcd cluster |\n\n## Integration Points\n\nKubernetes uses etcd to store the Lease objects themselves. When a Kubernetes controller runs leader election, it:\n1. Creates/updates a Lease object in etcd using Kubernetes API\n2. etcd replicates this Lease across the cluster using Raft\n3. The controller observes the Lease field to determine if it holds leadership\n\nThis creates a layered architecture where etcd's Raft provides durability, while Kubernetes' lease-based election provides application-level coordination."
